      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary><h3>How often are dividends paid?</h3></summary>
        <p>Most U.S. companies pay dividends on a quarterly basis (four times a year). However, some companies, particularly Real Estate Investment Trusts (REITs), pay monthly, while others may pay semi-annually or annually.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary><h3>What is a good dividend yield?</h3></summary>
        <p>A 'good' dividend yield typically ranges between 2% and 6%. Yields significantly higher than this (e.g., above 8%) can sometimes be a warning sign of a distressed company or an unsustainable payout.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary><h3>Can you live off dividend investing?</h3></summary>
        <p>Yes, but it requires substantial capital. For example, to generate $40,000 a year in passive income from a portfolio yielding 4%, you would need $1,000,000 invested.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary><h3>Are dividends guaranteed?</h3></summary>
        <p>No, dividends are never guaranteed. A company's board of directors must declare them, and they can be reduced or eliminated entirely if the company faces financial difficulties.</p>
      </details>
    </div>
